Here's a C# code example using the `HttpClient`, `M3uParser`, and `File` classes to download the live stream segments. To run this code, you'll need to install the `M3uParser` NuGet package. You can install it through the Package Manager Console in Visual Studio with the command:

```
Install-Package M3uParser
```

Below is the C# code example:

```csharp
using System;
using System.IO;
using System.Net.Http;
using System.Threading.Tasks;
using M3uParser;

class Program
{
    static readonly HttpClient httpClient = new HttpClient();
    static readonly string playlistUrl = "https://path-to-your-live-stream/playlist.m3u8";

    static async Task Main()
    {
        while (true)
        {
            try
            {
                var response = await httpClient.GetAsync(playlistUrl);

                if (!response.IsSuccessStatusCode)
                {
                    Console.WriteLine("Failed to retrieve playlist. Retrying in 5 seconds.");
                    await Task.Delay(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
                    continue;
                }

                var content = await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync();
                var parser = new M3uParser.M3uFile();
                await parser.ReadFromStringAsync(content);
                var playlist = parser.MediaFiles;

                foreach (var segment in playlist)
                {
                    Uri segmentUrl = new Uri(segment.Path);
                    var segmentData = await httpClient.GetByteArrayAsync(segmentUrl);
                    var segmentFilename = Path.GetFileName(new Uri(segment.Path).LocalPath);

                    await File.WriteAllBytesAsync(segmentFilename, segmentData);

                    Console.WriteLine($"Downloaded {segmentUrl}");
                }

                var waitTime = TimeSpan.FromSeconds(parser.TargetDuration);
                await Task.Delay(waitTime);
            }
            catch (Exception ex)
            {
                Console.WriteLine($"Error: {ex.Message}. Retrying in 5 seconds.");
                await Task.Delay(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
            }
        }
    }
}
```

Similar to the Python example, this script will attempt to download segments as they become available from the live stream. Make sure to start this script as close to the beginning of the live stream as possible to capture as many segments as you can. Also, remember that a dedicated video player, recording tool, or server-side recording solution is preferred to ensure a complete and seamless recording of live streams.
